  imageAlt="A compact Australian home office with organised paperwork and desk supplies"
>
  <p>
    A home desk often becomes the filing cabinet for the whole household. Current work competes
    with school notices, bills, spare leads, manuals and receipts until the surface has no clear
    owner.
  </p>
  <p>
    Empty it and separate active work from household administration, occasional supplies and
    genuine archive material. Each group has a different access pattern; treating them as one
    office category is what makes a small filing cabinet feel full.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep current work closest, give essential records an appropriate home and move surplus tech
    or bulk supplies off the desktop. Storage should follow that hierarchy rather than preserve
    every paper pile beside the laptop.
  </p>

  <h2>Let the Desk Belong to Current Work</h2>
  <p>
    Home office storage should start with access, not furniture. The daily items
    need a close home; the occasional items need a findable home; the old
    paperwork usually does not need to sit beside the laptop.
  </p>
  <p>
    A clear surface, one home for daily supplies, labelled tech storage and a separate paperwork
    system will often outperform a large unit that mixes every category together.
  </p>

  <h2>Empty the Desk and Name Each Category</h2>
  <p>
    Before buying storage, sort the home office items into practical groups. This
    avoids buying a product that looks useful but does not match the clutter you
    actually have.
  </p>
  <p>Common home office storage categories include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Current paperwork.</li>
    <li>Archive paperwork.</li>
    <li>Notebooks and stationery.</li>
    <li>Laptop accessories.</li>
    <li>Chargers and spare cables.</li>
    <li>Printer paper and ink.</li>
    <li>Headphones, webcams and microphones.</li>
    <li>External drives and USB accessories.</li>
    <li>Product manuals and warranty paperwork.</li>
    <li>Receipts and household documents.</li>
    <li>Cleaning cloths and small desk supplies.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Each group needs different access. A pen used daily should not be stored the
    same way as old paperwork. A spare HDMI cable does not need the same position
    as a laptop charger. If your broader workspace is still being planned, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/home-office-setup-ideas-small-spaces/">home office setup guide for small spaces</a>{" "}
    is a useful starting point before choosing storage furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>Use Frequency to Set the Storage Distance</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li><strong>Daily:</strong> current papers, notebook, pen, charger and headphones within easy reach.</li>
    <li><strong>Occasional:</strong> spare leads, printer supplies, extra notebooks and call accessories in a nearby drawer, shelf or labelled box.</li>
    <li><strong>Archive:</strong> completed files, old receipts and retained records away from the active desk when appropriate.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This hierarchy is more useful than treating every item as urgent. It also reveals whether the
    workspace needs furniture or simply a better location for the archive.
  </p>

